Thanks.

00:20:54.839 --> 00:20:55.839
Awesome.

00:20:55.839 --> 00:20:59.839
Yeah, so my question was around, I think you mentioned something about

00:21:00.839 --> 00:21:04.839
collecting some data files from the lab using Shiny.

00:21:04.839 --> 00:21:09.839
So I was just wondering if you could talk about the process around

00:21:09.839 --> 00:21:14.839
identifying Shiny as the correct tool to do this and then whether you

00:21:14.839 --> 00:21:18.839
had any interaction with the stakeholder to get approval for using it

00:21:18.839 --> 00:21:24.839
and then as an add on to that, what development challenges did you meet,

00:21:24.839 --> 00:21:27.839
if any, when using Shiny in enterprise?

00:21:28.839 --> 00:21:29.839
Thanks.

00:21:29.839 --> 00:21:30.839
Yeah.

00:21:30.839 --> 00:21:31.839
Okay.

00:21:31.839 --> 00:21:36.839
So basically, why using Shiny?

00:21:36.839 --> 00:21:39.839
It's because we're using R to start with.

00:21:39.839 --> 00:21:44.839
So basically, the data analysis that I've been doing, we have an internal

00:21:44.839 --> 00:21:50.839
package that is called Nestat that I participated to in developing some

00:21:50.839 --> 00:21:52.839
code around design of experiment analysis.

00:21:53.839 --> 00:22:02.839
And so just to say that we have a rather intense activity using R as the

00:22:02.839 --> 00:22:08.839
software for doing our analysis, especially when it comes to, you know,

00:22:08.839 --> 00:22:13.839
sometimes from the lab, you can have some more and more automatic or

00:22:13.839 --> 00:22:18.839
semi-automatic equipment that would generate a lot of data like

00:22:18.839 --> 00:22:23.839
photo samplers, like robotic systems and things like this.

00:22:23.839 --> 00:22:28.839
And when it comes to that, you have a lot of different files or a lot of

00:22:28.839 --> 00:22:29.839
files, which are not so different.

00:22:29.839 --> 00:22:32.839
They are the same structure, but it's a lot of them.

00:22:32.839 --> 00:22:37.839
And, you know, copy pasting it in Excel and trying to do something out of

00:22:37.839 --> 00:22:40.839
that is kind of painful.

00:22:40.839 --> 00:22:45.839
And so very quickly when I come to this situation, I would then start

00:22:45.839 --> 00:22:49.839
coding in R to do the loading, automatic data running, put things together,

00:22:49.839 --> 00:22:53.839
have a nice graph with nice colors using ggplot and so on.

00:22:53.839 --> 00:22:56.839
So I'm a tidyverse fan, by the way.

00:22:56.839 --> 00:23:01.839
And then with this, you have your code.

00:23:01.839 --> 00:23:05.839
And then you get your colleague from the lab or from the project management

00:23:05.839 --> 00:23:06.839
saying, Hey, that's very nice.

00:23:06.839 --> 00:23:09.839
But now I have new files and I would like to do it again.

00:23:09.839 --> 00:23:14.839
And the same analysis and the same display and then over and over and over.

00:23:14.839 --> 00:23:18.839
So after some time you say, Hey, look, I can just package that into a nice

00:23:18.839 --> 00:23:20.839
web interface.

00:23:20.839 --> 00:23:23.839
And then you can do it all on your own.

00:23:23.839 --> 00:23:26.839
And then if there is anything going wrong, then you can just let me know.

00:23:26.839 --> 00:23:30.839
And I will also then update it.

00:23:30.839 --> 00:23:34.839
Other things that could happen, typically to give you an example of why

00:23:34.839 --> 00:23:39.839
we've been doing this is, so while you sort of secret that a coffee machine

00:23:39.839 --> 00:23:43.839
is pushing water through a system and then with water you have also some

00:23:43.839 --> 00:23:44.839
pressure.

00:23:44.839 --> 00:23:47.839
And then so you have some curves of pressure against time or temperature

00:23:47.839 --> 00:23:49.839
against time, this kind of thing.

00:23:49.839 --> 00:23:57.839
And then we are interested in what is the maximum here, what is the plateau

00:23:57.839 --> 00:24:00.839
here, what is the local minimum, what is the local thing and what is the

00:24:00.839 --> 00:24:01.839
variability.

00:24:01.839 --> 00:24:05.839
So all these features extracted that are then directed into that.

00:24:05.839 --> 00:24:08.839
And then they would run their own analysis on the features.

00:24:08.839 --> 00:24:10.839
But you need to extract these features.

00:24:10.839 --> 00:24:14.839
And a typical shiny app would be something where they could upload the

00:24:14.839 --> 00:24:17.839
raw data and then get back a CSV file where they have the features

00:24:17.839 --> 00:24:20.839
analyzed and extracted.

00:24:20.839 --> 00:24:27.839
So now how did we manage to have this in the company?

00:24:27.839 --> 00:24:33.839
So I would say a key thing is to have a good relationship with IT because

00:24:33.839 --> 00:24:37.839
they are the guardians of the compliance for IT and it's really important

00:24:37.839 --> 00:24:41.839
and for very good reasons, especially in a company as exposed as big

00:24:41.839 --> 00:24:45.839
companies, I would say any big company.

00:24:45.839 --> 00:24:52.839
And while it went, so the first thing that's, I mean at some point I had

00:24:52.839 --> 00:24:56.839
also, you can also have shiny apps that you just like locally deploy in

00:24:56.839 --> 00:25:02.839
the computer and then you can also have your colleague having R installed

00:25:02.839 --> 00:25:07.839
and then you can just, we started by this sometimes, by the way, to have

00:25:07.839 --> 00:25:14.839
kind of a batch file to just start the process and then double click on it

00:25:14.839 --> 00:25:18.839
and then it would open automatically R and shiny behind and then they would

00:25:18.839 --> 00:25:19.839
have the page.

00:25:19.839 --> 00:25:23.839
But then it's sitting on their computer and if we want to update anything

00:25:23.839 --> 00:25:26.839
then we need to go to their computer again.

00:25:26.839 --> 00:25:30.839
So there were some discussion also already from the center where people

00:25:30.839 --> 00:25:33.839
were saying, you know, that would be interesting and then, you know,

00:25:33.839 --> 00:25:38.839
connecting with IT, you manage to put it into the sufficiently secret and

00:25:38.839 --> 00:25:42.839
closed environment but still available in the intranet.

00:25:42.839 --> 00:25:49.839
And then more recently we moved with Azure and then it goes into Azure

00:25:49.839 --> 00:25:53.839
with Azure solutions.

00:25:53.839 --> 00:25:57.839
And then that's also where you can manage the access, you can manage the

00:25:57.839 --> 00:25:59.839
visibility of the virtual machine.

00:25:59.839 --> 00:26:03.839
So now we choose the server, it's about the virtual machine.

00:26:03.839 --> 00:26:11.839
And, yeah, so the thing is to have our IT counterparts that are aligned

00:26:11.839 --> 00:26:13.839
with this.

00:26:13.839 --> 00:26:16.839
So basically what I was looking at, so I could describe the needs that we

00:26:16.839 --> 00:26:21.839
had as programmers and data scientists and then they would, they came back

00:26:21.839 --> 00:26:25.839
with some proposal and then we moved together to have something that's up

00:26:25.839 --> 00:26:28.839
and running.

00:26:28.839 --> 00:26:37.839
So I don't know if I covered the whole question because you asked me also,

00:26:37.839 --> 00:26:41.839
yeah, how do we, is there any hurdles in the big company?

00:26:41.839 --> 00:26:49.839
Yeah, we said it's just having the right people but it's also a matter of

00:26:49.839 --> 00:26:54.839
good compromise, I would say, because of course you are not in the world

00:26:54.839 --> 00:26:59.839
of open source and or you would not, typically our code is versioned into

00:26:59.839 --> 00:27:03.839
a Git system but inside, in-house, we would not put our code on GitHub

00:27:03.839 --> 00:27:06.839
because it's a private company.

00:27:06.839 --> 00:27:11.839
So you need to have this understanding and then also explaining what are

00:27:11.839 --> 00:27:13.839
the needs that we have.

00:27:13.839 --> 00:27:17.839
Typically in R&D we have some needs that are inherent to research and

00:27:17.839 --> 00:27:19.839
development.

00:27:19.839 --> 00:27:21.839
We cannot predict what we will discover because it's research and

00:27:21.839 --> 00:27:23.839
development.

00:27:23.839 --> 00:27:29.839
And sometimes this is a bit difficult to handle when you speak with people

00:27:29.839 --> 00:27:34.839
who are used to deploying an app and the app is doing what it's supposed

00:27:34.839 --> 00:27:38.839
to be doing and we know everything and there is no doubt and that goes

00:27:38.839 --> 00:27:40.839
with it.

00:27:40.839 --> 00:27:42.839
So there was also these discussions around that to really understand

00:27:42.839 --> 00:27:48.839
each other's needs and perspective because you cannot either go freely

00:27:49.839 --> 00:27:54.839
and say, I'm R&D, I'm creative, I want to do everything and you need to

00:27:54.839 --> 00:27:58.839
play by the rules for the good reason and understand them.

00:27:58.839 --> 00:28:02.839
Regarding your comment about good relationships with IT and Travis, I

00:28:02.839 --> 00:28:04.839
see you made a comment.

00:28:04.839 --> 00:28:06.839
We do hear that a lot.

00:28:06.839 --> 00:28:10.839
I like to ask what are some concrete steps or things that you can do to

00:28:10.839 --> 00:28:15.839
actually build a good relationship with IT because sometimes it can be a

00:28:15.839 --> 00:28:18.839
statement akin to deliver a great customer experience.

00:28:18.839 --> 00:28:22.839
What does that actually mean and look like?

00:28:22.839 --> 00:28:31.839
I would say, yeah, the good relationship with IT is I would say like any

00:28:31.839 --> 00:28:37.839
human relationship, it's understanding also the other's perspective.

00:28:38.839 --> 00:28:46.839
It's really, you know, most of the time, really in the very vast majority

00:28:46.839 --> 00:28:52.839
when someone is bothering us with some constraints, it's not by pleasure or

00:28:52.839 --> 00:28:54.839
just to make our life worse.

00:28:54.839 --> 00:28:58.839
It's because they need to deliver on something and they are also

00:28:58.839 --> 00:29:05.839
accountable for something and then we need to make sure that we also speak

00:29:05.839 --> 00:29:09.839
the same language but at least we have a common ground of understanding.

00:29:09.839 --> 00:29:12.839
I would say that would be one of the key things.

00:29:12.839 --> 00:29:19.839
I remember, for instance, yeah, there might be things that you are not

00:29:19.839 --> 00:29:26.839
aware of typically on some of the data access or some of the systems access.

00:29:26.839 --> 00:29:30.839
You say, you know, I would like to have it open in the words of sharing,

00:29:30.839 --> 00:29:33.839
sharing knowledge, sharing science, sharing everything.

00:29:34.839 --> 00:29:38.839
And then they say, yeah, but you see, this and this can happen and actually

00:29:38.839 --> 00:29:40.839
it did already happen and you didn't know that.

00:29:40.839 --> 00:29:45.839
So listen to the stories also that they have to tell us where it comes from,

00:29:45.839 --> 00:29:49.839
all these frame that was put in place.

00:29:49.839 --> 00:29:55.839
And afterwards, it's even better because once it's well set, then you can

00:29:55.839 --> 00:30:00.839
really work in a confident manner in a safe environment.

00:30:00.839 --> 00:30:05.839
So, yeah, I would say understand and listen to the other, but also be able

00:30:05.839 --> 00:30:12.839
to explain your perspective and your needs in a most objective way,

00:30:12.839 --> 00:30:13.839
I would say.

00:30:13.839 --> 00:30:20.839
Bottom line is to say, yeah, I need to, this is how I see them.

00:30:20.839 --> 00:30:24.839
And I see someone is commenting one good relationship with IT.

00:30:24.839 --> 00:30:25.839
Do not lose patience.

00:30:25.839 --> 00:30:27.839
Yes, absolutely.

00:30:27.839 --> 00:30:29.839
Losing patience is also a good thing.

00:30:29.839 --> 00:30:33.839
But yes, I'm not saying I'm succeeding every time.

00:30:33.839 --> 00:30:37.839
Sometimes I'm, you know, passionate, I would say.

00:30:37.839 --> 00:30:41.839
But yes, it's try to understand also their perspective.

00:30:41.839 --> 00:30:44.839
I want to go to the anonymous questions.

00:30:44.839 --> 00:30:47.839
There's a few of them.

00:30:47.839 --> 00:30:50.839
One is, do you miss supervising people?

00:30:50.839 --> 00:30:52.839
Do you still supervise people?

00:30:52.839 --> 00:30:55.839
I find that it seems like an inevitable path to progress, but I don't know

00:30:55.839 --> 00:30:57.839
if I'd be any good.

00:30:57.839 --> 00:31:00.839
That's a good question because that's exactly one of the reasons I moved

00:31:00.839 --> 00:31:02.839
also to Nestle.

00:31:02.839 --> 00:31:10.839
So I think it's inevitable to do some sort of supervision.

00:31:10.839 --> 00:31:18.839
Now, the great thing is I have the chance to have in Nestle that we have a

00:31:18.839 --> 00:31:20.839
path where we can develop expertise.

00:31:20.839 --> 00:31:22.839
And that's what I've chosen.

00:31:22.839 --> 00:31:26.839
I'm not developing into managing more and more people, having a group and a

00:31:26.839 --> 00:31:28.839
department and an institute or whatever.

00:31:28.839 --> 00:31:32.839
I'm more developing the expertise in data science.

00:31:32.839 --> 00:31:37.839
But still, with a certain level of seniority, people come to you and ask

00:31:37.839 --> 00:31:41.839
you for help, ask you for feedback, ask you for having some, you know,

00:31:41.839 --> 00:31:44.839
can you have a look at what I've done and then tell me?

00:31:44.839 --> 00:31:48.839
And then also people ask you, well, from your perspective, what strategic

00:31:48.839 --> 00:31:50.839
decision would you recommend?

00:31:50.839 --> 00:31:58.839
At some point, you take this also span when you grow in the career.

00:31:58.839 --> 00:32:05.839
So that's why I say it's inevitable to do some sort of management.

00:32:05.839 --> 00:32:13.839
So I would say I don't have direct people as of now, but I have, you know,

00:32:13.839 --> 00:32:17.839
indirect or dotted line type of relationship also.

00:32:17.839 --> 00:32:22.839
I may supervise sometimes some students or in case like this.

00:32:22.839 --> 00:32:30.839
But it's more, yeah, something I would say like coaching and

00:32:30.839 --> 00:32:35.839
counselor type of activity.

00:32:35.839 --> 00:32:38.839
Still with the responsibility that goes with it because I've got the

00:32:38.839 --> 00:32:44.839
experience sometimes that I've got some feedback where, yeah, senior leader

00:32:44.839 --> 00:32:48.839
would ask some project manager who is presenting the project.

00:32:48.839 --> 00:32:49.839
So these are the conclusions.

00:32:49.839 --> 00:32:51.839
And then, oh, did you check it with Jean-Vincent?

00:32:51.839 --> 00:32:54.839
And then if they say yes, then you say, oh, OK.

00:32:54.839 --> 00:32:55.839
That's right.

00:32:55.839 --> 00:32:59.839
So you're kind of the validation of the expertise.

00:32:59.839 --> 00:33:02.839
And it goes with the responsibility because if it fails behind, then

00:33:02.839 --> 00:33:04.839
that's somehow also your credibility that is at stake.

00:33:04.839 --> 00:33:09.839
But I would say that, yeah, that's really something that is occurring,

00:33:09.839 --> 00:33:11.839
I would say, in any career.

00:33:11.839 --> 00:33:12.839
There was an anonymous question.

00:33:12.839 --> 00:33:14.839
I think it referred to a previous conversation.

00:33:14.839 --> 00:33:17.839
It's what is a head of technology?

00:33:17.839 --> 00:33:22.839
I guess the implied question is like, well, what does that entail?

00:33:22.839 --> 00:33:31.839
Well, that is exactly in this line of not having a typical direct report.

00:33:31.839 --> 00:33:37.839
At the time, I was transversal into the different groups.

00:33:38.839 --> 00:33:43.839
And so I would be the go-to person if there was a technological question

00:33:43.839 --> 00:33:45.839
in the company.

00:33:45.839 --> 00:33:50.839
And then also trying to coordinate across the different groups

00:33:50.839 --> 00:33:52.839
of different activities.

00:33:52.839 --> 00:33:58.839
So that would mean reviewing what the different engineers are doing,

00:33:58.839 --> 00:34:05.839
giving them also some feedback on the results,

00:34:05.839 --> 00:34:10.840
saying maybe also some guidance on how they would do the next experiment

00:34:10.840 --> 00:34:16.840
or how they would address the next process challenge.

00:34:16.840 --> 00:34:23.840
And then, yeah, also being the counselor for a relationship with outside.

00:34:23.840 --> 00:34:27.840
So when someone is coming and saying, okay, I would like to do this new

00:34:27.840 --> 00:34:29.840
implant with that technology.

00:34:29.840 --> 00:34:32.840
Do you think you can bring me a solution with this?

00:34:32.840 --> 00:34:37.840
